                    </div>
                    <div class="clear"></div><br  />

                    <p class="greenColor bgNone">
                        You may experience tobacco withdrawal symptoms after quitting. Withdrawal symptoms are uncomfortable physical and psychological experiences felt after breaking tobacco addiction. Identify your withdrawal symptoms and overcome them with these tips!
                    </p>

                    <ul class="tabList">
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Irritable mood –</span>
                            Relax by taking a bath or walk, or listen to soft music</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Tiredness – </span>
                            Take a nap and don’t take any extra work</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Having sleep disturbances – </span>
                            Avoid caffeine and use mind relaxation techniques like yoga	and music</li>

                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Dry throat and cough – </span>
                            Drink plenty of water</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Hunger – </span>
                            Eat healthy balanced meals with lots of fiber and drink lots of water </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Find difficulty concentrating – </span>
                            Take lot of breaks</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Feel tightness of chest – </span>
                            Take a few rhythmic breaths</li>


                    </ul>


                    <div class="headText">
                        Managing cravings
                    </div>
                    <div class="clear"></div><br  />
                    <p class="greenColor bgNone">
                        Cravings are the strong urge to smoke or chew tobacco. Identify events or situations that trigger a desire to smoke and plan ahead to overcome them with these tips:
                    </p>

                    <ul class="tabList">
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Boredom  –</span>
                            Learn a new hobby or engage in your favorite activity</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Having breakfast – </span>
                            Change the time or place</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">With tea or coffee – </span>
                            Change the time or place of your regular cuppa or switch your drink</li>

                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">After meals? – </span>
                            Chew mint, elaichi, saunf and take a walk or nap</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">With certain friends – </span>
                            Explain your reasons for quitting and meet in no-smoking places </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">With certain locations  – </span>
                            Avoid locations that prompt smoking</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">While driving – </span>
                            Listen to music, chew gums or candies</li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="textHighlight">Stressful work situations – </span>
                            Simplify your work schedule, take frequent breaks, get support from colleagues</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p class="tabNote">Remember that the cravings die after few minutes and becomes weaker with every passing day.</p>

